Final Answer:

Here is a suggested playlist of 7 songs to introduce someone to jazz, showcasing the evolution of the genre chronologically:

1. "West End Blues" - Louis Armstrong (1928)
   https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_End_Blues

2. "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" - Duke Ellington (1932)
   https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/It_Don%27t_Mean_a_Thing_(If_It_Ain%27t_Got_That_Swing)

3. "Body and Soul" - Coleman Hawkins (1939)
   https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Body_and_Soul_(1930_song)

4. "Round Midnight" - Thelonious Monk (1944)
   https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%27Round_Midnight

5. "So What" - Miles Davis (1959)
   https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/So_What_(Miles_Davis_composition)

6. "Take Five" - Dave Brubeck (1959)
   https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Take_Five

7. "A Love Supreme" - John Coltrane (1964)
   https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Love_Supreme

This playlist covers a range of jazz styles from early New Orleans jazz to modal jazz and avant-garde, highlighting key developments in the genre over nearly four decades.

